    "narrative": "For today\u2019s slate, **Mickey Moniak** leads the way with a stellar 75.75 score, bolstered by a massive +14% park adjustment and a prime matchup against Mike Burrows. The high efficiency is driven by a favorable platoon advantage and a move into the #2 hole, making him our highest-upside play for Runs and RBI. Close behind are **Jazz Chisholm Jr.** (73.11) and **James Wood** (73.10). **Jazz Chisholm Jr.** benefits from Civale\u2019s mediocre xERA and the added stolen base potential against an average defensive catcher, while **James Wood** is a must-start thanks to his high-leverage leadoff spot and a strong +10% order bonus against Liberatore. **Vinnie Pasquantino** also cracks the top tier (72.59) despite historical BvP headwinds, as his elite platoon splits against Williams provide the necessary floor to overcome those minor negative indicators.\n\n**Corbin Carroll** remains a priority start at 68.01, specifically because his speed metrics are weaponized by a slow-working Peralta. With a 92% steal projection against this battery, he is our premier choice for safeguarding our lead in the scarcest category. On the flip side, we are exercising caution with **Gabriel Moreno** (49.93) and **Josh Naylor** (50.89); both face difficult matchups against tough arms in Peralta and Eovaldi, respectively. While they remain in the lineup due to lack of superior alternatives, their scores reflect the difficulty of the individual matchups. **Austin Riley** carries the most uncertainty, as his 61.77 score assumes a #4 spot in a lineup that is still pending; should he drop down the order, his utility diminishes rapidly.\n\nThe most difficult bench decision involved **Zach McKinstry**, who finished just outside the starting cut with a 50.73 score. While he benefits from the same favorable Civale matchup as **Jose Caballero**, **Jose Caballero** maintains a higher base projection and situational utility that kept him in the #9 slot. We are opting to keep **Zach 